{{Forms of government}} '''Bankocracy''' (from the English word [[bank]] and [[Ancient Greek]] κράτος - ''kratos'', "power, rule") or '''trapezocracy'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yanisvaroufakis.eu/2011/03/02/the-road-to-bankruptocracy-how-events-since-2009-have-led-to-a-new-mode-of-reproduction/ |title=The Road to Bankruptocracy: How events since 2009 have led to a new mode of reproduction |author=[[Yanis Varoufakis]] |date= 2 March 2011|work= |publisher= |accessdate=19 September 2012}}</ref> (from Greek τράπεζα - ''trapeza'', "bank") is a polemic term referring to the excessive power or influence of [[bank]]s on [[public policy]]-making.<ref>{{cite news |title=Britain is ruled by the banks, for the banks |author=Chakrabortty, Aditya |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2011/dec/12/britain-ruled-by-banks |newspaper=The Guardian |date= 12 December 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> It can also refer to a [[form of government]] where [[financial institution]]s rule society.
==Usage== One of the first uses of the term was by British Member of Parliament [[William Fullarton]] (1754–1808), who in a parliamentary debate on April 10, 1797 characterized the monopoly of the [[Bank of England]] as being a more important issue to solve than the peace attempts to end the [[Campaigns of 1797 in the French Revolutionary Wars|war against France]]:<ref>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1790-1820/member/fullarton-william-1754-1808 FULLARTON, William (1754-1808), of Fullarton, Ayr. | History of Parliament Online]</ref> {{cquote|It is Bankocracy that threatens the destruction of social order ... that turns and overturns all questions respecting war, negotiations, and peace.}}
United States Senator [[Robert J. Walker]] (1801–1869), a staunch opponent of the [[Second Bank of the United States|Bank of the United States]], delivered a speech in the [[US Senate|Senate]] on January 21, 1840, where he warned that the acceptance of [[Banknote|paper money]] as legal tender would "overthrow the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]], subvert the liberties of the country, and the rights of the people, and establish the reign of a bankocracy, more sordid, ruinous, and despotic, than that of any monarch, however absolute."<ref>{{cite book |title=Speech of Mr. Walker, of Mississippi, on the bill to provide for the collection, safe-keeping, and disbursement of the public money: Senate U.S. January 21, 1840. |last1=Walker|first1= Robert J.|authorlink=Robert J. Walker |year=1840 |publisher= |location= |isbn= |page=13|url=http://hdl.handle.net/2027/wu.89095783668 |accessdate=September 18, 2012 }}</ref>
[[Pierre-Joseph Proudhon]] used the term in his work ''Les Confessions d’un révolutionnaire'' (1849), in reference to the [[July Monarchy]]:<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/w/index.php?title=Confessions_of_a_Revolutionary/5 Proudhon, Pierre-Joseph (1849). Confessions of a Revolutionary V. 1830-1848: Government Corruption]</ref> {{cquote|The principle of the July government, founded by and for the middle class, was therefore property, the capital. Under a monarchical form, the essence of that government was ''bankocracy''.}}
The term was also used by [[Karl Marx]] in his work ''[[Das Kapital|Das Kapital, Kritik der politischen Ökonomie]]'' (1867). He theorizes the birth of [[national debt]] as the catalyst for the [[primitive accumulation of capital]]:<ref>[http://www.marxists.org/archive/marx/works/1867-c1/ch31.htm Marx, Karl (1867). Capital, Vol. I. Chapter Thirty-One: Genesis of the Industrial Capitalist]</ref> {{cquote|The public debt becomes one of the most powerful levers of primitive accumulation. ... [T]he national debt has given rise to joint-stock companies, to dealings in negotiable effects of all kinds, and to agiotage, in a word to stock-exchange gambling and the modern bankocracy.}}
In [[Marxian economics]], the term cognates with [[finance capitalism]] in general.<ref>{{cite book |title=Dictionary of Philosophical Terms vol. II - English-German / Englisch-Deutsch |last1=Waibl |first1=Elmar|last2=Herdina|first2=Philip|authorlink= |year=1997 |publisher= Walter de Gruyter|location= |isbn=3110979497 |page= 345|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r7OiXFVasZEC&dq=bankokratie&source=gbs_navlinks_s&redir_esc=y |accessdate=September 18, 2012 }}</ref>
Numerous political observers and journalists have used the term when describing or commenting on the [[2007–2012 global financial crisis]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lanchester |first1=John |last2= |first2= |year=2009 |title= Bankocracy |journal=[[London Review of Books]] |volume=31 |issue= 21|pages= 35–36|publisher= |doi= |url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/v31/n21/john-lanchester/bankocracy |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>[[University of Leicester]] - '[http://www2.le.ac.uk/ebulletin/events/2010-2019/2012/feb/npevent.2012-01-25.0792876682 Against Bankocracy: Bank ownership, regulation and growth]' event</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.davidmcwilliams.ie/2011/01/12/citizens-must-fight-rise-of-european-bankocracy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114215911/http://www.davidmcwilliams.ie/2011/01/12/citizens-must-fight-rise-of-european-bankocracy |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2011-01-14 |title=Citizens must fight rise of European bankocracy |author=[[David McWilliams (economics pundit)|David McWilliams]] |date=12 January 2011 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=19 September 2012 }}</ref>
