{{Terrorism}}[[File:Frente Sur Contras 1987.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Contras]] in Nicaragua, 1987]]
[[File:Flag of Lord's Resistance Army.svg|thumb|upright|Flag of the [[Lord's Resistance Army]]]]

In international relations '''violent non-state actors''' ('''VNSA''') (also known as '''non-state armed actors''' or '''non-state armed groups''') are individuals and groups that are wholly or partly independent of [[state government]]s and which threaten or use violence to achieve their goals.{{Sfn|Hofmann and Schneckener|2011|p=2-3}}

VNSAs vary widely in their goals, size, and methods. They may include [[Illegal drug trade|narcotics cartels]], popular [[liberation movements]], religious and ideological organizations, [[corporations]] (e.g. [[Private military company|private military contractors]]), self-defence [[militia]], and [[Paramilitary|paramilitary groups]] established by state governments to further their interests.{{Sfn|Hofmann and Schneckener|2011|p=2-3}}{{Sfn|Chatham House|2016|p=8}}

While some VNSAs oppose governments, others are allied to them.{{Sfn|Hofmann and Schneckener|2011|p=2-3}} Some VNSAs are organized as paramilitary groups, adopting methods and structure similar to those of state [[Military|armed forces]]. Others may be informally structured and use violence in other ways, such as kidnapping, using [[improvised explosive device]]s, or [[Security hacker|hacking]] into computer systems.

==Description==
{{See also|Non-state actor}}

[[File:Mara_Salvatrucha_Graffiti.jpg|thumb|upright|[[MS-13]] gang graffiti.]]

Thomas, Kiser, and Casebeer asserted in 2005 that "VNSA play a prominent, often destabilizing role in nearly every humanitarian and political crisis faced by the international community".{{sfn|Thomas|Kiser|Casebeer|2005|p={{page needed|date=October 2012}}}} As a new type of actor in international relations, VNSAs represent a departure from the traditional [[Westphalian sovereignty]] system of states in two ways: by providing an alternative to state governance; and by challenging the state's [[monopoly of violence]].

Phil Williams stated in 2008 that in the 21st century, they "have become a pervasive challenge to nation-states".<ref name="violentnonstatep4">{{harvnb|Williams|2008|p=4}}.</ref> Williams argues that VNSAs develop out of poor state governance but also contribute to the further undermining of governance by the state. He explains that when weak states are "unable to create or maintain the loyalty and allegiance of their populations", "individuals and groups typically revert to or develop alternative patterns of affiliation".<ref name="violentnonstatep6" /> This causes the family, tribe, clan or other group to become "the main reference points for political action, often in opposition to the state".<ref name="violentnonstatep6" /> According to Williams, globalization has "not only... challenged individual state capacity to manage economic affairs, it has also provided facilitators and force multipliers for VNSAs".<ref name="violentnonstatep6">{{harvnb|Williams|2008|p=6}}.</ref> Transnational flows of arms, for example, are no longer under the exclusive surveillance of states. Globalization helps VNSAs develop transnational social capital and alliances as well as funding opportunities.<ref name="violentnonstatep6-7">{{harvnb|Williams|2008|p=6—7}}.</ref>

The term has been used in several papers published by the [[US military]].{{sfn|Casebeer|Thomas|2002}}{{sfn|Bartolomei|Casebeer|Thomas|2004}}{{sfn|Thomas|Casebeer|2004}}{{sfn|Shultz|Farah|Lochard|2004|}}

== Types ==
Some common and influential types of VNSAs include:
* Criminal organizations. [[Drug cartel]]s, for example, may carry out assassinations, kidnappings, thefts, extortions; operate protection rackets; and [[wikt:turf war|defend their ''turf'']] from rival groups and the military.
* [[Social movement|People's movements]] or sections of them that have chosen [[Guerrilla warfare|guerrilla tactics]] (also known as [[asymmetric warfare]]) to pursue their aims. An example is the [[Naxalite–Maoist insurgency|Naxalite-Maoist insurgency]] in central India.{{Sfn|Economist|2006|p=}}
* [[Private military company|Private military companies]], and corporations that either have their own, or hire, private military services.{{Sfn|Daugaard|2012|p=}} An example is [[Floating armoury|floating armouries]] in the Indian Ocean.{{Sfn|Holtom and Chapsos|2015|p=}}
* Religious or ideological groups, such as [[Boko Haram]] in and around Nigeria, that espouse armed violence as a moral or sacred duty.{{Sfn|Drake|1998|p=}}{{Sfn|UN Secretary-General|2017|p=30-31}}
* Citizen militia, which may form to protect a locality from (or threaten it with) attack, such as the [[Anti-balaka|anti-balaka movement]] in the Central African Republic.{{Sfn|Child Soldiers International|2016b|p=4}}
* [[Paramilitary]] groups, which make use of military methods and structures to pursue their agenda, such as the now-decommissioned Irish Republican Army.
* [[Warlord]]s, who are leaders using armed violence to exercise military, economic, and political control over territory within a sovereign state. Warlords have a long history in Afghanistan, for example.{{Sfn|Coll|2004|p=4}}
Phil Williams, in an overview article, identifies five types of VNSAs:<ref name="violentnonstatep9-16">{{harvnb|Williams|2008|p=9—16}}.</ref>
* [[Warlord]]s
* [[Militia]]s
* [[Insurgency|Insurgencies]]
* [[List of designated terrorist organizations|Terrorist organizations]]
* [[Criminal organization]]s and gangs

== Relationship to terrorism ==
There is no commonly accepted [[Definitions of terrorism|definition of "terrorism"]],{{Sfn|Emmerson|2016|p=10-11}}{{Sfn|Halibozek et al|2008|p=4-5}}{{Sfn|Williamson|2009|p=38}} and the term is frequently used as a political tactic to denounce opponents whose status as [[Terrorism|terrorists]] is disputed.{{Sfn|Sinclair and Antonius|2012|p=14}} An attempt at a global definition appears in the working draft of Comprehensive Convention Against International Terrorism, which defines terrorism as a type of act, rather than as a type of group.{{Sfn|UN General Assembly|2005|p=8-9}} Specifically, "terrorism" in the draft refers to the threatened or actual intentional injury to others, and serious damage to property resulting in major economic loss:{{quote|when the purpose of the conduct, by its nature or context, is to intimidate a population, or to compel a Government or an international organization to do or to abstain from doing any act.{{Sfn|UN General Assembly|2005|p=8-9}}}}

Since the definition encompasses the actions of some violent non-state actors (and of some state actors) and not others, disagreements remain and the treaty has yet to be agreed, {{as of|lc=yes|2015}}.{{Sfn|European Parliament|2015|p=}} For example, the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] has called for acts of terrorism to be distinguished from:{{quote|the legitimate struggle of peoples under foreign occupation and colonial or alien domination in the exercise of their right to [[self-determination]] in accordance with the principles of [[international law]]".{{Sfn|European Parliament|2015|p=}}}}

== Use of children ==

{{See also|Children in the military|Child soldiers in Africa|Impact of war on children}}

Violent non-state actors have drawn international condemnation for relying heavily on children under the age of 18 as combatants, scouts, porters, spies, informants, and in other roles{{Sfn|Child Soldiers International|2016a|p=}}{{Sfn|UN Secretary-General|2017|p=}} (although many state armed forces also recruit children).{{Sfn|Child Soldiers International|2012|p=}} In 2017, for example, the United Nations identified 14 countries where children were widely used by armed groups: Afghanistan, Colombia, [[Child soldiers in the Central African Republic|Central African Republic]], [[Child soldiers in the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Democratic Republic of the Congo]], Iraq, Mali, Myanmar, Nigeria, The Philippines, [[Child soldiers in Somalia|Somalia]], South Sudan, Sudan, Syria, and Yemen.

Not all armed groups use children, and approximately 60 that used to do so have entered agreements to reduce or end the practice since 1999.{{Sfn|Child Soldiers International|2016a|p=4}} For example, by 2017 the [[Moro Islamic Liberation Front]] (MILF) in the [[Philippines]] had released nearly 2,000 children from its ranks,{{Sfn|UNICEF|2017|p=}} and the [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia|FARC-EP]] guerilla movement in Colombia agreed in 2016 to stop recruiting children.{{Sfn|UN Secretary-General|2017|p=41}} In other situations, the use of children was increasing in 2017, particularly in Afghanistan, Iraq, Nigeria and Syria, where Islamist militants and groups opposing them intensified efforts to recruit children.{{Sfn|Human Rights Watch|2016|p=}}{{Sfn|UN Secretary-General|2017|p=}}

==Humanitarian engagement==

Researchers at the [[Overseas Development Institute]] propose that engagement with VNSAs, which they call armed non-state actors, is essential to humanitarian efforts in conflicts. They claim that it is often necessary to do so to facilitate access to those affected and to provide humanitarian assistance.{{sfn|Jackson|2012}} However, humanitarian agencies often fail to engage strategically with VNSAs. This tendency has strengthened since the end of the Cold War, partly because of the strong discouragement of humanitarian engagement with VNSAs in counterterrorism legislation and donor funding restrictions. In their opinion, further study is necessary to identify ways in which humanitarian agencies can develop productive dialogue with VNSAs.{{sfn|Jackson|2012}}

The International Security Department and the International Law Programme at Chatham House are seeking to understand the dynamics that will determine support for a principle-based approach to engagement by humanitarian actors with VNSAs.{{sfn|''Chatham House''}}

